# PostgreSQL LISTEN / NOTIFY

> **Requires a running PostgreSQL** on `localhost:5432` (adjust the `url` above).
> This example is not part of the test suite — H2/SQLite have no LISTEN/NOTIFY,
> so the receive path only works against real Postgres. Run with `ssc run`.

The **publish** side already works via `Db.query` and `SELECT pg_notify(channel, payload)`.
The **receive** side needs a connection that stays open and is drained with
`getNotifications()` — `Db.query`/`Db.execute` open and reuse one cached connection
per database name (`ConnectionRegistry`), so `Db.pgListen` registers `LISTEN` on it
and a later `Db.getNotifications` on the *same* database name drains what arrived.

## Run

```scalascript
// Start listening on the "events" channel.  Cached per db name, so the LISTEN
// stays registered for subsequent getNotifications calls on "default".
Db.pgListen("default", "events")

// Publish on the same channel.  A connection that is both LISTENing and NOTIFYing
// receives its own notification (self-delivery), so this round-trips on one conn.
val _ = Db.query("default", "SELECT pg_notify(?, ?)", ["events", "hello-from-ssc"])

// Drain: block up to 1000 ms for notifications delivered to the listening conn.
// Each entry is a Map { channel, payload, pid }.
val notes = Db.getNotifications("default", 1000)

notes.foreach { n =>
  println("channel=" + n("channel") + " payload=" + n("payload") + " pid=" + n("pid"))
}

// Stop listening when done.
Db.unlisten("default", "events")

println("pg-listen-notify: received " + notes.length + " notification(s)")
```
